| footnotes                 = 
| box_width                 = 
}}The '''disappearance of Mar<U+00ED>a Esther Aguilar Cansimbe''' happened 11 November 2009 when the female newspaper journalist who worked for ''El Diario de Zamora'' and ''El Cambio de Michoac<U+00E1>n'' in [[Michoac<U+00E1>n]], [[Mexico]] vanished. Her disappearance may or may not be linked to her coverage of the [[Mexican Drug War]] but both [[Article 19]] and [[Reporters Without Borders]], two international press freedom organizations, have classified her disappearance as an act of [[Forced disappearance|enforced disappearance]].<ref name=rsf>{{cite web|url=http://en.rsf.org/mexico-one-month-after-journalist-s-11-12-2009,35318.html |title=One month after journalist<U+2019>s disappearance, investigation seems to go nowhere - Reporters Without Borders |publisher=En.rsf.org |date= |accessdate=2013-10-01}}</ref>
She is one of 4 journalists and the only woman to have disappeared between 2006 and 2010 in the state of Michoac<U+00E1>n where the drug war began.<ref>{{cite news|title=Threats and censorship at peak in Veracruz, Oaxaca, Michoac<U+00E1>n and Zacatecas |publisher=Pressenza |date=September 30, 2013 |accessdate=2013-11-11 |url=http://www.pressenza.com/2013/09/threats-and-censorship-at-peak-in-veracruz-oaxaca-michoacan-and-zacatecas/}}</ref>
== Personal ==

Mar<U+00ED>a Esther Aguilar Cansimbe resided in  [[Zamora, Michoac<U+00E1>n|Zamora]], Michoac<U+00E1>n, Mexico. She married police chief David Silva, a former public security director in [[Jacona, Michoac<U+00E1>n|Jacona]], and had two daughters, ages eleven and thirteen.<ref name=rsf /><ref name=rsfinitial /><ref name=cpj2/>

== Career ==

Mar<U+00ED>a Esther Aguilar Cansimbe wrote for two Michoac<U+00E1>n newspapers as a police reporter for ''El Diario de Zamora'', which is an [[Organizacion Editorial Mexicana]] owned newspaper, and for the [[Morelia|Morelia-based]] ''El Cambio de Michoac<U+00E1>n''' as its local correspondent.<ref name=cpj2>{{cite web|author=Silence or Death in Mexico's Press |url=http://www.cpj.org/reports/2010/09/silence-death-mexico-press-timeline.php |title=Silence or Death in Mexico's Press - Reports - Committee to Protect Journalists |publisher=Cpj.org |date= |accessdate=2013-10-01}}</ref><ref name=cpj>{{cite web|url=http://www.cpj.org/2009/11/mexican-crime-reporter-vanishes-in-western-michoac.php |title=Mexican crime reporter vanishes in western Michoac<U+00E1>n - Committee to Protect Journalists |publisher=Cpj.org |date= |accessdate=2013-10-01}}</ref><ref name=sipiapa />

Aguilar was a journalist for 10 years and as a police reporter for 4 years and often dealt with the criminal underworld and corruption in local government.<ref name=rsfinitial /><ref name=cpj /><ref name=amcostarica /> In the months before her disappearance, she had reported on corrupt military and police officers working in conjunction with local criminal groups and the imprisonment of members of a Mexican drug cartel, which is known as [[La Familia Michoacana]].<ref name=cpj /><ref name=amcostarica />

== Disappearance ==

