Aguilar disappeared on 11 November 2009.<ref name=amcostarica>{{cite web|url=http://www.amcostarica.com/112309.htm |title=Costa Rica newspaper: A.M. Costa Rica: Your English language daily news source |publisher=A.M. Costa Rica |date= |accessdate=2013-10-01}}</ref><ref name=pressenza>{{cite web|url=http://www.pressenza.com/2011/07/woman-journalistxs-murder-turns-veracruz-into-deadliest-state-for-media-this-year/ |title=Woman journalist<U+2019>s murder turns Veracruz into deadliest state for media this year |publisher=Pressenza |date= |accessdate=2013-10-01}}</ref> She left her home in Zamora after receiving a phone call from an unknown source.<ref name=amcostarica /> All phone calls made to Aguilar's phone later failed to connect.<ref name=sipiapa>{{cite web|author=Name * |url=http://www.sipiapa.org/en/iapa-calls-for-swift-action-to-locate-missing-mexican-journalist/ |title=IAPA calls for swift action to locate missing Mexican journalist &#124; SIP <U+2013> Sociedad Interamericana de Prensa |publisher=Sipiapa.org |date=2009-11-20 |accessdate=2013-10-01}}</ref> Days before her disapearance, she had published a story about the arrest of a local drug trafficker.<ref name=knightcenter>{{cite web|url=https://knightcenter.utexas.edu/archive/blog/?q=en/node/5862 |title=Mexican police reporter vanishes after reporting arrest of crime boss &#124; Journalism in the Americas |publisher=Knightcenter.utexas.edu |date= |accessdate=2013-10-01}}</ref> After 72 hours, her family reported her as missing to the authorities.<ref name=sipiapa />  Prior to her disappearance, many of her colleagues were believed {{who|date=November 2013}} to have been bribed and intimidated by officials and drug traffickers to cease their investigative reporting. Aguilar, however, had continued to write her articles despite this.<ref name=englishpen>{{cite web|url=http://www.englishpen.org/mexico-a-tribute-to-maria-esther-aguilar-cansimbe/ |title=[Mexico&#93; A tribute to Maria Esther Aguilar Cansimbe |publisher=Englishpen.org |date= |accessdate=2013-10-01}}</ref>
== Context ==

The state Michoac<U+00E1>n had become well known for its high levels of crime and government misconduct.<ref name=peninternational>{{cite web|url=http://pen-international.org/newsitems/mexico-crime-reporter-missing/ |title=PEN International <U+2013> MEXICO: Crime reporter missing |publisher=Pen-international.org |date= |accessdate=2013-10-01}}</ref>
== Impact ==

She is one of thirty-two writers who have been murdered or declared missing after covering Mexican drug-traffickers.<ref name=theglobeandmail>{{cite web|author=Alex Neve and Marian Botsford Fraser |url=http://m.theglobeandmail.com/commentary/pressing-ahead-on-journalistic-freedom/article1367189/?service=mobile |title=Pressing ahead on journalistic freedom - The Globe and Mail |publisher=M.theglobeandmail.com |date=2012-08-23 |accessdate=2013-10-01}}</ref>
Aguilar's disappearance is one of many that has caused outcry from the several press freedom organizations.Her case has been classified as enforced disappearance. This is covered under the International Convention for the Protection of All Persons from Enforced Disappearance enacted by the [[United Nations General Assembly]]. The convention that has been ratified by 26 of 91 nations.<ref name=umuvugizi>{{cite web|url=http://www.umuvugizi.com/?p=3550&lang=en |title=RSF calls countries to respect law on enforced disappearance |publisher=Umuvugizi |date= |accessdate=2013-10-01}}</ref>
She is one of at least 4 journalists from Michoac<U+00E1>n alone that have been killed or reported missing in that state.<ref name=sipiapa /><ref name=rsfinitial>{{cite web|title=Journalist Missing for One Week in Michoac<U+00E1>n Sate |publisher=Reporters Without Borders |date=November 19, 2009 |accessdate=2013-01-11 |url=http://en.rsf.org/mexico-journalist-missing-for-one-week-in-19-11-2009,35048.html}}</ref> Before Aguilar's disappearance, [[Jos<U+00E9> Antonio Garc<U+00ED>a (journalist)|Jos<U+00E9> Antonio Garc<U+00ED>a Apac]] went missing on 20 November 2006 and Mauricio Estrada Zamora disappeared on 12 February 2008. Five months after Aguilar's disappearance, Ram<U+00F3>n <U+00C1>ngeles Zalpa, who also worked for the ''Cambio de Michoac<U+00E1>n'' disappeared.<ref name=insinewssafety>{{cite web|url=http://www.newssafety.org/news.php?news=18509&cat=mexico-media-safety |title=INSI: News |publisher=Newssafety.org |date=2003-04-09 |accessdate=2013-10-01}}</ref><ref name=thepanamanews>{{cite web|url=http://www.thepanamanews.com/pn/v_16/issue_05/opinion_10.html |title=Reporters Without Borders, Journalist who reported on Mexican violence disappears |publisher=Thepanamanews.com |date=2010-04-11 |accessdate=2013-10-01}}</ref>
== Reactions ==

Within a week of her disappearance, the Committee to Protect Journalists had contacted authorities asking for their aid in safely locating Aguilar.  Some journalists who had worked with her stated that her disappearance was directly related to her work.<ref name=cpj /> Jes<U+00FA>s Montejano Ram<U+00ED>rez, the local state prosecutor, told the Milenio newspaper that a investigation was being underwent but that he could not reveal the names of any potential suspects.<ref name=cpj /> The Office of the Special Prosecutor for Crimes against Journalists dependent on the Federal Attorney<U+2019>s Office was put in charge of this investigation.<ref name=article19>{{cite web|author=Article 19 |title=Written comments of Article 19: Global Campaign for Freedom of Expression |date=March 2011 |accessdate=2013-11-11 |url=http://www.article19.org/data/files/pdfs/submissions/mexico-for-the-consideration-at-the-93rd-session-of-the-un-working-group-on-.pdf}}</ref>

